The new anti-globalization backlash
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt at the latest G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of the world's major developed economies' leaders, no one can say which among them will be part of the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The backlash against globalization has lasted for two decades.
By the late 20th century, the global trend seemed to be toward convergence, and people appeared to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking the stores of this chain became a standard form of protest against globalization.
But recently, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is increasingly interconnected, there is a sense that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are becoming more sophisticated), companies are relocating their production closer to markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
This kind of "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese automobiles. They then began producing these automobiles domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are made in the United States. But the reversal of globalization of goods is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotics engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, the current criticism of globalization tends to focus less on trade issues.
But this evolution does not reflect only the slowdown in trade growth.
Rich consumers are much more comfortable with foreign products; in some cases, they even depend on them, from constantly updated electronics to cheap "fast fashion," which has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, today's opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on issues of obscure courts protecting foreign companies' interests and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
Then there is the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety over this influx may be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are people in advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they have never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people worldwide head to advanced countries each year.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we tend more towards quick and superficial experiences rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches, a single interaction is very different from ongoing contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to travel today is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are unlikely to provide good or even honest service to people who will surely never return.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers defraud you, hoteliers lie about their facilities.
Moreover, this little game can be interrupted.
In places where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it also becomes a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes can lead to significant economic destabilization.
Tourism businesses respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The symbol of modern tourism is a giant cruise ship, where passengers can spend just a few hours at each destination (visiting a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleeping in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean ship, Harmony of the Seas, aims to replicate all climates of the world.
In fact, this over 30-meter-long ship, which contains the Eiffel Tower, features a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Bus or train tourism companies do the same to ensure the safety of their customers, letting them off at famous sites for only a limited time, just long enough to take some photos.
This style of travel imposes constraints on local infrastructure capacity.
There often isn't enough space to walk along Venice's canals or along the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstandings.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meeting only scammers who offer them nonsense or expensive taxi rides.
The locals do not appreciate groups of tourists who gather around their most beautiful sites.
Noone feels particularly involved, nor does anyone maintain any sense of trust.
It's easy to feel nostalgic for a time when tourism went hand in hand with long stays and extended encounters with very different cultures.
Of course, it would be impossible for the current number of visitors to stay weeks or months at a time in old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain arrangements in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
For example, Airbnb can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel or, worse still, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7, living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
Soon after entering World War II, Winston Churchill famously moved into the White House for 24 days to strengthen the transatlantic alliance between Britain and the United States, deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of today's globalist populists.
